today.

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:35.500
Sometimes, in order to save and honor something
we cherish, we have to shit on it."

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:36.500
[laughter]

00:13:36.500 --> 00:13:37.500
You're mad at me over there.

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:38.500
I can tell.

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:39.500
So, yes.

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:41.089
That, I would think, justifies.

00:13:41.089 --> 00:13:44.089
It gives me the political cover to write this
book.

00:13:44.089 --> 00:13:49.290
I was also amused, as you might have seen
just a few weeks ago, the maintenance crew

00:13:49.290 --> 00:13:52.110
at Independence Hall in Philadelphia where
the Liberty Bell is.

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:57.200
I had spent an entire day and a half adding
a protective shellac to the outside of the

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:58.200
Liberty Bell.

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:02.079
And I can't help but think, knowing as we
do now, where the Liberty Bell has been.

00:14:02.079 --> 00:14:06.150
They're about 240 years too late.

00:14:06.150 --> 00:14:09.240
The Founders actually knew this.

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:14.019
And most of them suspected at the end of that
time in Philadelphia that the Constitution

00:14:14.019 --> 00:14:20.200
that they wrote by September is, as the kids
might say, a bit of a hot mess.

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:26.139
For starters, this venerated document doesn't
mention the word "slavery" or the word "democracy"

00:14:26.139 --> 00:14:28.270
or even "Facebook."

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:32.620
It plays favorites among the states, giving
Wyoming as many Senators as New York.

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:34.350
And I mean, come on.

00:14:34.350 --> 00:14:39.600
It has typos and misspellings and a smudge
that, and this is true, may or may not be

00:14:39.600 --> 00:14:43.660
a comma empowering the government to seize
your house depending on which Constitutional

00:14:43.660 --> 00:14:45.500
scholar you ask.

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:49.620
It is, as we know, scrawled with the quill
of a goose on the skin of a goat.

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:55.180
And its Preamble, its famous Preamble, its
most famous introductory passage was written

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:58.949
by delegate Gouverneur Morris, a man with
a peg-leg.

00:14:58.949 --> 00:15:01.129
They called him the Peg Leg Morris.

00:15:01.129 --> 00:15:06.759
And while his Preamble is notoriously beautiful,
it nonetheless, gives our sacred Constitution

00:15:06.759 --> 00:15:08.550
hardly a leg to stand on.

00:15:08.550 --> 00:15:09.550
People.

00:15:09.550 --> 00:15:10.550
OK.

00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:11.550
There we go.

00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:12.550
Groan if you must and you should.

00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:13.579
But the Founders knew this, too.

00:15:13.579 --> 00:15:17.399
And in fact, by the way, just so you know,
New York is number one.

00:15:17.399 --> 00:15:18.589
I should say this.

00:15:18.589 --> 00:15:24.389
I spent some time in Article 4, which the
Article 4 is actually supposed to referee

00:15:24.389 --> 00:15:25.529
disputes among the states.

00:15:25.529 --> 00:15:27.610
And sometimes it doesn't do such a great job.

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:31.870
So, I decided the only way to really solve
the problem is to go ahead and rank the states

00:15:31.870 --> 00:15:32.870
already.

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:34.720
Now, I ranked New York as number one, obviously.

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:39.670
But depending how the rest of this afternoon
goes, I'm just saying, we could fall a few

00:15:39.670 --> 00:15:40.670
spots.

00:15:40.670 --> 00:15:44.730
George Washington himself, George Washington
himself, the man who presided over the Constitutional

00:15:44.730 --> 00:15:49.620
Convention, agrees with me about the flaws
in the Constitution.

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:52.340
It was he who predicted that the flawed Constitution
would become controversial.

00:15:52.340 --> 00:15:54.040
"A child of fortune," he said.

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:56.829
"To be fostered by some but buffeted by others."

00:15:56.829 --> 00:16:00.930
And when the Constitutional Convention was
over, he said explicitly, quote "I wished

00:16:00.930 --> 00:16:03.580
it had been made more perfect."

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:08.810
Benjamin Franklin himself stomached it only
quote "with all its faults."

00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:12.170
And in fact, on the very last day of the Constitutional
Convention, George Washington, excuse me,

00:16:12.170 --> 00:16:15.730
Benjamin Franklin gave a speech that I think
somewhat hilariously sums up what he really

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:17.860
probably thought about their handiwork that
day.

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:22.660
It was in the same speech where he said that
he wished everyone would doubt their infallibility

00:16:22.660 --> 00:16:24.830
and put their name to the measure.

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:28.810
And he finished the speech by saying this,
and I think--.

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:31.850
You just need to read in-between the lines
a little bit, see what he's really saying

00:16:31.850 --> 00:16:35.329
to understand what he actually felt about
the four months of compromise that they had

00:16:35.329 --> 00:16:36.329
just done.

00:16:36.329 --> 00:16:42.360
He says, quote "I confess that there are several
parts of this Constitution which I do not

00:16:42.360 --> 00:16:44.180
at present approve.

00:16:44.180 --> 00:16:47.670
But I am not sure I shall never approve them.

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:52.300
I doubt whether any other convention we can
obtain may be able to make a better Constitution.

00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:58.490
Thus, I consent to this Constitution because
I expect no better.

00:16:58.490 --> 00:17:04.659
And because I am not sure that it is not the
best," which you might say he sounds like

00:17:04.659 --> 00:17:06.860
a Republican endorsing Mitt Romney.

00:17:06.860 --> 00:17:07.860
[laughter]

00:17:07.860 --> 00:17:08.860
Exactly.

00:17:08.860 --> 00:17:10.529
Damning with faint praise.

00:17:10.529 --> 00:17:15.410
Whereas, unlike my book, which I hope people
understand the true intent as Justice Scalia

00:17:15.410 --> 00:17:16.410
did.

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:18.010
And I'll talk about him a little bit later.

00:17:18.010 --> 00:17:20.020
That I'm hopefully praising with faint damnation.

00:17:20.020 --> 00:17:21.839
You'll see that I actually come back around.

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:22.839
I don't want to spoil the ending.

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:25.130
I don't want to tell you that the butler did
or didn't do it.

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:26.860
But if anything, only the accomplice.

00:17:26.860 --> 00:17:30.080
And I'll get to that a little bit, too.

00:17:30.080 --> 00:17:36.360
Because as these Founders knew, while we think
of the Constitution as yes, the painstakingly

00:17:36.360 --> 00:17:41.620
designed blueprint drawn up by what Thomas
Jefferson called "an assembly of demigods,"

00:17:41.620 --> 00:17:44.650
who laid the foundation for the sturdiest
republic ever created.

00:17:44.650 --> 00:17:46.260
All true.

00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:51.730
By the end of that summer in Philadelphia,
the framers knew the truth that the Constitution

00:17:51.730 --> 00:17:54.130
was not exactly a blueprint.

00:17:54.130 --> 00:17:58.250
They would have agreed that it was a bit of,
and I use this phrase as I wrote it a year

00:17:58.250 --> 00:18:00.700
ago, a bit of an Etch-A-Sketch.

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:02.630
A haphazard series of blunders.

00:18:02.630 --> 00:18:07.510
They admitted that they had to shake clean
and redraw dozens of times during a sweltering

00:18:07.510 --> 00:18:13.520
summer of petty debates, drunken ramblings,
wild improvisation, and desperate compromise.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:14.520
You have to imagine it.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:16.470
They were, I mean, we had this last weekend
in New York, right?

00:18:16.470 --> 00:18:17.610
It was miserably hot.

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:19.980
And Philadelphia was even hotter.

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:24.890
And they were there for four months in the
sweltering summer of Philadelphia wearing

00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:27.230
powdered wigs, wool coats.

00:18:27.230 --> 00:18:28.230
They locked the doors.

00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:30.190
They shuttered the windows for privacy.

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:32.220
There was no such thing as air-conditioning.

00:18:32.220 --> 00:18:33.740
It was an unventilated room.

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:36.919
There was a prison riot right across the street.

00:18:36.919 --> 00:18:40.770
Butchers were throwing animal carcasses that
they were done with, truly, within feet of

00:18:40.770 --> 00:18:42.279
the Pennsylvania State House.

00:18:42.279 --> 00:18:43.279
So, you can imagine.

00:18:43.279 --> 00:18:45.130
it was pungent all over the place.

00:18:45.130 --> 00:18:48.570
Not to mention that they were, in fact, drinking
beer for breakfast.

00:18:48.570 --> 00:18:52.429
Now, the truth of the matter is, most people
drank beer for breakfast because it was cleaner

00:18:52.429 --> 00:18:53.429
than water.

00:18:53.429 --> 00:18:56.559
But nonetheless, the fact remains, they were
drinking beer for breakfast.

00:18:56.559 --> 00:19:00.950
And in fact, you don't actually have to--.

00:19:00.950 --> 00:19:07.210
I do a pretty lengthy explanation of what
actually transpired during those four months.

00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:13.750
And I conclude, and I explain how it all concluded
as well, if I can find the page because my

00:19:13.750 --> 00:19:14.840
bookmark has disappeared.

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:17.110
It's now over here somewhere.

00:19:17.110 --> 00:19:22.750
Ah, there we go.

00:19:22.750 --> 00:19:24.170
[pause]

00:19:24.170 --> 00:19:25.580
Hmm.

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:29.820
There we go.

00:19:29.820 --> 00:19:33.710
So again, after four months.

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:35.480
Now we understand how it all happened.

00:19:35.480 --> 00:19:37.970
Or rather, almost didn't.

00:19:37.970 --> 00:19:42.169
The Constitution wasn't only a miracle at
Philadelphia, written by an assembly of demigods.

00:19:42.169 --> 00:19:44.490
It was that, but it was also the contrary.

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:49.610
What began as a measured, deliberate effort
to rescue a beleaguered country became a perpetual

00:19:49.610 --> 00:19:54.800
unresolved motion machine--a maddening cycle
of non-binding votes by a parade of toothless

00:19:54.800 --> 00:20:00.190
committees, marked by fits and starts, fights
and full-stops, conducted by a combative group

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:08.049
of exhausted, drunken, broke, petty, partisan,
scheming, squabbling, bloviating, back-stabbing,

00:20:08.049 --> 00:20:14.760
grandstanding, god-forsaken, posturing, restless,
cow-tipping, homesick, cloistered, claustrophobic,

00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:19.350
sensory-deprived, under-oxygenated, fed up,
talked out, overheated delegates so distraught

00:20:19.350 --> 00:20:23.760
and despairing they threatened violence, secession,
foreign allegiance and even prayer.

00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:27.580
As Benjamin Franklin said, "and concluded
for those who didn't abandon the proceedings

00:20:27.580 --> 00:20:32.289
altogether, with as much pre-meditation and
forethought as a game of musical chairs.

00:20:32.289 --> 00:20:37.020
The last, least abhorrent, mutually somewhat
acceptable idea on the table when the music

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:41.039
stopped, or the heat became too unbearable,
or the liqueur too strong, or the rioting

00:20:41.039 --> 00:20:45.870
too loud, or the pressure too intense, or
the company too loathsome, or the wigs too

00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:52.410
uncomfortable, or the patience too thin, became
the law of the land" as much the product of

00:20:52.410 --> 00:20:57.480
yes, an assembly of demigods as yes, some
might say a confederacy of what could be dunces

00:20:57.480 --> 00:20:58.750
on occasion.

00:20:58.750 --> 00:21:03.860
From page one, the Constitution is, by its
own admission, a great compromise.

00:21:03.860 --> 00:21:06.980
It is also what you get when you drink beer
for breakfast.

00:21:06.980 --> 00:21:10.850
Now, amusingly, they didn't just drink beer
for breakfast.

00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:15.610
I'm actually understating that because the
truth of the matter is they drank a lot of

00:21:15.610 --> 00:21:17.010
beer at that time.

00:21:17.010 --> 00:21:20.070
They drank a lot of everything at that time.

00:21:20.070 --> 00:21:23.800
The statistics are astounding, but I'll just
point this out.

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:27.330
When they finally decided what was gonna be
in the Constitution, and they knew they were

00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:30.350
about to sign it, well, they threw a party,
'cause they knew that they'd finally be able

00:21:30.350 --> 00:21:32.409
to bid adieu to each other.

00:21:32.409 --> 00:21:34.920
But this is what happened that night.

00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:39.080
They were about to add their signatures to
an extremely anticipated official document

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:42.190
that many of them had extremely mixed feelings
about.

00:21:42.190 --> 00:21:45.320
So the delegates did what anyone might do
under such pressure.

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:47.520
They drank themselves silly.

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:50.680
After they toasted the occasion, they drowned
their miseries.

00:21:50.680 --> 00:21:54.090
They had spent four months compromising some
of their values, perhaps they could drink

00:21:54.090 --> 00:21:55.409
their guilt away.

00:21:55.409 --> 00:21:56.960
They certainly tried.

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:01.799
In the span of just a few hours, the 55 men
who crowded City Tavern on Friday, September

00:22:01.799 --> 00:22:07.010
14th, 1787, guzzled enough alcohol to fell
an Army Regiment.

00:22:07.010 --> 00:22:08.710
Sixty bottles of claret.

00:22:08.710 --> 00:22:10.520
Fifty-four bottles of Madeira.

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:12.460
Fifty bottles of old stock.

00:22:12.460 --> 00:22:19.380
Vats of porter, cider, and beer, and what
has been described as "some" bowls of rum.

00:22:19.380 --> 00:22:21.320
They weren't just pledging their sacred honor.

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:23.220
They were pledging a frat.

00:22:23.220 --> 00:22:27.630
So wild did the celebration get, the City
Tavern, a place quite familiar with drunkenness,

00:22:27.630 --> 00:22:32.130
took the unusual step of sending along a bill
for quote unquote "breakage."

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:34.350
Pretty amusing to me.

00:22:34.350 --> 00:22:37.850
Honestly, the miracle at Philadelphia is that
the Constitution wasn't written on the back

00:22:37.850 --> 00:22:38.850
of a bar napkin.

00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:40.210
That's a big question.

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:44.740
Which actually brings me to my drinking companion,
as I had just mentioned.

00:22:44.740 --> 00:22:52.409
What are the more fortunate accidents really
in getting to research and write this book

00:22:52.409 --> 00:22:55.130
was getting to have lunch with Justice Scalia.

00:22:55.130 --> 00:23:01.510
Now, of course, as you can understand, I wanted
to meet with Justice Scalia because I thought

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:06.940
who on the face of the planet, let alone in
the country, would really be most amenable

00:23:06.940 --> 00:23:10.840
to a page one rewrite of the Constitution?

00:23:10.840 --> 00:23:15.149
And you gotta assume it's the man who's devoted
his entire life to protecting every phrase,

00:23:15.149 --> 00:23:17.809
clause, and punctuation in it.

00:23:17.809 --> 00:23:21.780
I was a little bit alarmed, or surprised,
I guess I should say, that he agreed to meet

00:23:21.780 --> 00:23:22.780
with me.

00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:25.289
But of course, also thrilled that he would.

00:23:25.289 --> 00:23:28.529
I should also say, of course, the truth of
the matter is that he actually agrees with

00:23:28.529 --> 00:23:29.529
Thomas Jefferson.

00:23:29.529 --> 00:23:31.990
Thomas Jefferson, who said the Constitution
be rewritten every 19 years.

00:23:31.990 --> 00:23:37.530
He doesn't agree with that part, but he agrees
with Jefferson that the Constitution is, and

00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:39.899
this is his words, "dead."

00:23:39.899 --> 00:23:42.990
The difference is, between him and Thomas
Jefferson, is that Justice Scalia means dead

00:23:42.990 --> 00:23:44.730
as a compliment, apparently.

00:23:44.730 --> 00:23:46.760
He means quit trying to revive it.

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:51.519
He means honor it for what we know it was
and adore it for all of those merits.

00:23:51.519 --> 00:23:55.649
So, he agreed to meet.

00:23:55.649 --> 00:23:59.049
And we did, in fact, talk of a lot of things
in the Constitution.

00:23:59.049 --> 00:24:03.980
But I knew at some point that I would have
to turn our attentions to his bread and butter--the

00:24:03.980 --> 00:24:09.020
Third Article, the judicial branch, where
of course he makes his living.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:12.929
And I had to, what I hope I do in this book
is address the actual issues that people have

00:24:12.929 --> 00:24:14.640
with the Articles and Amendments.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:15.909
My solutions are rather absurd.

00:24:15.909 --> 00:24:19.429
But I do address the actual issues.

00:24:19.429 --> 00:24:24.070
And one of the issues that people have with
the Third Amendment, excuse me, the Third

00:24:24.070 --> 00:24:25.990
Article, the Supreme Court, is this idea.

00:24:25.990 --> 00:24:27.770
And when I mention these words, you could
see what happened.

00:24:27.770 --> 00:24:32.490
I broached the subject and I said, "Well,
Justice, Your Honor, you know that some people

00:24:32.490 --> 00:24:34.429
have a problem with lifetime ten--."

00:24:34.429 --> 00:24:38.809
And as soon as I got to ten--, he picked up
a fork, poked it at me and with a devilish

00:24:38.809 --> 00:24:39.940
grin said, "Don't you dare.

00:24:39.940 --> 00:24:42.299
Don't you dare change lifetime tenure.

00:24:42.299 --> 00:24:46.049
And if you do, at least grandfather me in
because I like my job."

00:24:46.049 --> 00:24:47.080
Fair enough.

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:48.419
But now here's the thing.

00:24:48.419 --> 00:24:54.090
The Constitution itself says nothing about
Supreme Court Justices having lifetime tenure.

00:24:54.090 --> 00:24:59.330
It merely says the Justices shall hold their
offices quote unquote "during good behavior."

00:24:59.330 --> 00:25:05.010
Now, for a bunch of very good reasons, early
on, we decided to interpret that as lifetime

00:25:05.010 --> 00:25:08.100
tenure because kings were removing judges
willy nilly from the bench.

00:25:08.100 --> 00:25:10.320
So, they thought, "Let's go the other way
with this."

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:13.049
But nonetheless, it doesn't actually say lifetime
tenure.

00:25:13.049 --> 00:25:15.670
It says merely during good behavior.

00:25:15.670 --> 00:25:21.580
And I felt it, my job, to say to him, "Well,
let's consider in 2012 whether or not we should

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:23.669
really still have lifetime tenure."

00:25:23.669 --> 00:25:27.220
And he put down the fork and agreed to listen
to me.

00:25:27.220 --> 00:25:29.640
And this is what transpired when that happened.

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:31.919
[clears throat]

00:25:31.919 --> 00:25:38.559
[reads from book]
"I don't bother lecturing Justice Scalia on

00:25:38.559 --> 00:25:40.160
any of this.

00:25:40.160 --> 00:25:45.370
After decades of legal study and 25 years
of service as one of America's top Judges,

00:25:45.370 --> 00:25:46.840
he's been fully briefed.

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:49.019
Instead, I begin my cross-examination.

00:25:49.019 --> 00:25:51.350
'How about you?'

00:25:51.350 --> 00:25:52.380
I ask.

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:55.710
'How about me what?' he counters.

00:25:55.710 --> 00:25:57.620
'Can you imagine just walking away?'

00:25:57.620 --> 00:25:58.620
I ask.

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:03.330
'Of course I can,' he scoffs, with a couldn't
care less tone that implies he'd just as soon

00:26:03.330 --> 00:26:08.410
leave today if only he hadn't signed a two-year
lease on his Supreme Court locker.

00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:09.950
'When?'

00:26:09.950 --> 00:26:12.059
I ask.

00:26:12.059 --> 00:26:15.519
Like I've said before, he says, 'As soon as
I'm not firing on all eight cylinders, when

00:26:15.519 --> 00:26:18.649
I'm not doing the job as well as I used to,
it'll be time to go.

00:26:18.649 --> 00:26:22.929
'How will you know when that is?'

00:26:22.929 --> 00:26:24.779
He looks me straight in the eye.

00:26:24.779 --> 00:26:25.850
'I'll know.'

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:30.230
'So, you don't need some outside authority
limiting the term of your servi--?'

00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:34.040
'I'm fairly aware of the requirements of the
position,' he interrupts me.

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:37.429
'I'll know when I can no longer fulfill them.'

00:26:37.429 --> 00:26:44.740
And yet, 'what if I told you, Your Honor,
that someone even more powerful than you says

00:26:44.740 --> 00:26:46.980
your wrong about that?'

00:26:46.980 --> 00:26:47.980
He looks at me.

00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:50.390
'And who is that?'

00:26:50.390 --> 00:26:53.149
'Someone you know quite well.'

00:26:53.149 --> 00:26:56.110
He looks at me again, wondering if he should
ask.

00:26:56.110 --> 00:26:57.679
'Who?'

00:26:57.679 --> 00:27:01.659
If this were a case in some courtroom drama,
