00:42:27.609 --> 00:42:33.309
&gt;&gt;Male #2: So, the one question I have, I
have a bunch, but I think the things I'm most

00:42:33.309 --> 00:42:37.430
curious about are, what did you find most
surprising about reading the document?

00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:41.670
What do you feel like is something that a
lot of Americans in general would be surprised

00:42:41.670 --> 00:42:43.550
to know is in the Constitution?

00:42:43.550 --> 00:42:48.160
&gt;&gt;Kevin: Just how, for lack of a better word,
dysfunctional, I guess is the regular word

00:42:48.160 --> 00:42:49.960
the Constitutional Convention itself was.

00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:53.730
I mean, it was a maddening cycle of compromise,
like I told you.

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:58.430
We know of it as the Great Compromise, but
we don't know that they did not make any decisions

00:42:58.430 --> 00:43:01.790
on what was going to be in the Constitution
until the very last minute.

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:04.500
And that was merely because they were so sick
of each other.

00:43:04.500 --> 00:43:09.190
They kept trying and trying over again and
they didn't address the Executive Branch until

00:43:09.190 --> 00:43:10.190
the middle of the summer.

00:43:10.190 --> 00:43:13.500
And even when they did, the famous phrase
is when they brought it up, a considerable

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:14.500
pause ensued.

00:43:14.500 --> 00:43:17.490
In other words, no one had any idea how to
design the Presidency.

00:43:17.490 --> 00:43:22.670
They literally started writing the Constitution
before they decided what was going to be in

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:23.670
it.

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:27.630
They got so sick of each other that they established
an even smaller committee, "style and arrangement"

00:43:27.630 --> 00:43:28.630
they called it.

00:43:28.630 --> 00:43:31.089
That was a group of, I forget, five or ten
people.

00:43:31.089 --> 00:43:34.010
But they would at night essentially say, "Well,
here's this.

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:35.010
Let's give this a shot."

00:43:35.010 --> 00:43:36.869
And then the next morning, they said, "How
does this look?

00:43:36.869 --> 00:43:37.869
Does it look good?"

00:43:37.869 --> 00:43:38.869
And they would actually vote on that.

00:43:38.869 --> 00:43:40.310
it's ultimately what they did.

00:43:40.310 --> 00:43:44.300
So, it's surprising to me that while we know,
of course, they were debating, we didn't know

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:47.579
that people like Luther Martin were getting
so drunk in the morning that he would give

00:43:47.579 --> 00:43:51.720
a six-hour speech and derail the Constitutional
Convention for two days.

00:43:51.720 --> 00:43:52.720
It's pretty astounding.

00:43:52.720 --> 00:43:54.880
That actual part of history was the most surprising
to me.

00:43:54.880 --> 00:43:56.040
I really enjoyed learning about it.

00:43:56.040 --> 00:43:59.670
And I think the joy in learning about it hopefully
is manifest on pages.

